<subSubSection id="C9C6F1F7FF74CEA4FCD5FDABD8803FBF" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8163A27CFF74CEA4FCD5FDABD8803FBF" blockId="249.[810,1452,634,984]" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF74CEA4FCD5FDABD8F73EBA" bold="true" box="[810,932,634,660]" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Females of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF74CEA4FBBAFDAADFA83EBA" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo" authorityYear="2016" box="[1093,1275,634,661]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cochabamba">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF74CEA4FBBAFDAADFA83EBA" box="[1093,1275,634,661]" italics="true" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">A. cochabamba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unique in the genus by the square-shaped post-labial sigilla (Ríos-Tamayo, 2016, fig. 2 B). They resemble to those of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF74CEA4FA6CFD12D8393F2E" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1917" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xenus">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF74CEA4FA6CFD12D8393F2E" italics="true" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">A. xenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the unilobated spermathecae receptacles but Males differ from those of the receptacles shape, which are parallel, subquadrate in 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF74CEA4FB8BFCFEDF8B3F66" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1917" box="[1140,1240,815,841]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xenus">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF74CEA4FB8BFCFEDF8B3F66" box="[1140,1240,815,841]" italics="true" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">A. xenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="19E7BEF9FF74CEA4FB13FCFFDE3C3F66" box="[1260,1391,814,840]" captionStart="FIGURE 214" captionStartId="236.[136,235,1180,1204]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,189,1157]" captionTargetId="figure-360@236.[151,1435,189,1157]" captionTargetPageId="236" captionText="FIGURE 214 A. Actinopus xenus Chamberlin, 1917, holotype, female: A MCZ 03: A. Spermathecae, dorsal view. Photo: R. Saturnino." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5597703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5597703/files/figure.png" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">Fig. 214 A</figureCitation>
) and divergent, conical in 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF74CEA4FBC7FC82DFA13F42" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo" authorityYear="2016" box="[1080,1266,850,877]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cochabamba">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF74CEA4FBC7FC82DFA13F42" box="[1080,1266,850,877]" italics="true" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">A. cochabamba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF74CEA4FAF3FC83D8363FBE" author="Rios-Tamayo, D." pageId="249" pageNumber="250" pagination="185 - 189" refId="ref140444" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. (2016) A new species of Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) from Bolivia. Revista del Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales, Nueva Serie, 18 (2), 185 - 189. https: // doi. org / 10.22179 / REVMACN. 18.444" type="journal article" year="2016">Ríos-Tamayo, 2016</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 2 E).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
